<font color="#FF0000">THOUGHTS ON SUBJECT</font><br>
<tt>Tue Jul 15 16:29:50 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
To all, especially Cook and Tom,<br><br>
I too have read the total Winter Soldier Investigation report and have the following comments to make on it and what has been said recently.<br><br>
  I'm sure that wrong doings happened, at certain times and certain places.  What I don't like about the Winter Soldier report is how it leads one to believe that such events were the norm or commonplace.  This is far from true.<br>
Yes, things happen, but I know or have met a large number of credible Vietnam Vets that would be willing to testify that in their units (Some were in the same units as some of the Winter Soldiers) such violence against civilians was almost non-existent.  So, who to believe?  How about this, according to Col. Harry G. Summers, Vietnam is made up &quot;a million truths&quot;, each truth being the perception of the individual person.  How about each person labels their experiences, as being just that, THEIR OWN.  The mistake about Vietnam in recent years, has been to project the worse case scenarios experienced by a few men into the overall group experience of them all.  All perceptions and experiences can be valid, but each is unique to the how the person perceives something and their own morals and background.  <br>
There have been incidents of violence and crimes carried out by military personnel.  These need to be studied in detail, in the hope they will never happen again, to be stopped before the happen.  There is no execuse for violence against civilains.  What everyone needs to remember is that war brings volunteers and conscripts, and that brings the best and worst of a society.  A army carries social problems (violence, murder, etc) with them.  Violence and crime by servicemen is not unique to this war, I can provide many examples from other wars and other countries.  For example, in World War II, 1,000 Americans were tried, convicted and executed for crimes, including murder.  My Grandfather was a driver/aide to a high ranking officer in the Burma, India, China theater in World War II.  he was witness to the court martial of a soldier for the robbery, rapes and murders of a couple of Burmese women.  This soldier was convicted and executed for his crimes.  Somehow, the crimes of a careless and distorted few are projected by some as the actions of all Vietnam vets.  This is a falsehood that needs to be corrected.  <br><br>
The real question of issue here, is DID THE POLICIES OF WAREFARE AND RULES OF ENGAGEMENTS AMONG SOME UNITS IN VIETNAM LEAD TO CARELESS OPERATIONS AND POOR PROCEDURES TO BE CARRIED OUT THAT RESULTED IN UNNECESSARY CIVILIAN CASUALTIES?  Vietnam was a war of body counts, a war where the enemy hid in civilian populations, the overall experience played right into Communist propoganda hands, that is truth, not a specualtion.  How much of the death and destruction on civilians was due to poor use of heavy firepower? How much to poor rules and procedures?  The only winning move in Vietnam was not to play?  When we hurt the very people we were sent to protect, it was time to quesion any involvement.  This idea is key to the civilain casualty issue in Vietnam, and sadly ALL wars lead to civilian deaths.<br><br>
I am not defending anyone or anything, but war breeds instances were personal judgement and circumstances force men to do things in self defense that would seem horrible to others not there?  What do you do if a child has a live hand grenade?  What do you do if you catch a woman boobytrapping something?  Here is a true story that happened to my father in 1970.  He was traveling to a remote site on a construction job, when they stopped in a village for a break.  While waiting, he and a small group of other guys had a experience where personal judgement was a major factor.  While they were waiting, a young Vietnamese child started running towards them with what appeared to be a hand grenade in his hand.  The men stopped cold and had a split second to choose a path of action.  Was this child sent with a hand grenade by the VC as other children were in the past (with US casualties) or is this something else.  Fortunately, the men held their fire and the hand grenade the child had turned out to be a used American smoke grenade.  The child was doing a good deed and returning it to Americans.  My father and the others guys thanked him and were glad nothing bad happened to anyone.  My question is how is a soldiers supposed to act and what is considered wrong?  What is self defense?   How difficult is it to fight a war of terorism of insurgency?  These are factors that need to be taken into account.  Each situation is different as is the reactions of each person.  The actions another group of soldiers may have taken may have been much more differnt.  This is all part of war.<br><br>
Also, for the record 201 Army soldiers and 77 Marines were court martialed for serious crimes against civilians.  Let's remember that in the end it is the peronal decisions of soldiers to commit these crimes.  Each person has their own set of morals that they have learned growing up.  How many of the soldiers who commited serious crimes in Vietnam, would have done so in the United States.  It should be noted that according to the Various criminal studies, only 1/2 of 1% of Vietnam vets are in jails at the current time.<br><br>
In regards to PTSD, it is something that happens to most everyone who engages in battle.  War is a sensory overload, the very worst of mankind (even if it is necessary).  But among men who have commited violent, unnecessary acts against civilians, I believe it is as much GUILT and Guilty feelings rather than true PTSD alone.<br><br>
Final thoughts on Winter Soldier:  It would be nice to have a concensus of opinion and persceptive in the units these men were part of.  Anyone can say anthing, and the time these hearings were done, the political spectrum was anti-war, which was taken by some as anti-warrior.  Also, with some many Vet wannabe's out their talking this stuff (many have been exposed as fakes by fellow Vets), and a anti-war movement that benefitted from having soldiers condemn fellow soldiers, how much of the details in this hearing are fact and how much of it is exaggeration?  How many of these men were really in Vietnam?  And if they were, how many were in places and settings where they could have experienced these acts?  Hearsay doesn't count!! <br><br>
 
